76561197978699116,Recommended,464850,29314290,Posted: 17 January,all,[Gold Pyro] francobaldo1,best game ever
,Not Recommended,464850,29519170,Posted: 27 January,all,agefreak,"TLDR;Pros:-1. Improved gameplay over DBC 142. Great control mechanics3. Highly customisable4. A fun cricket game....Cons:-1. .... which is plagued by lack of production finesse2. Abysmal commentary3. Plenty of in-game glitches, which tend to get frustrating4. Lots of issues from DBC 14 carried overMy verdict: Buy it if you must have a fun cricket game to play right now, else wait for a decent discount and a couple of patches / updates.7/10DBC 17 comes nearly three years after DBC 14 broke new grounds in creating a fun yet challenging cricket game for all platforms, something which the biggies of the gaming industry *cough*EA*cough* had considered too demeaning for them to take up. DBC 14 was a genuinely fun game, but it had its issues, some of which were never resolved. Of course, the success of DBC 14 meant that the next iteration had to be big enough to live up to the high standards set by the studio.Sadly, I cannot give a convincing thumbs up to this iteration of the game. A lot has improved - batting is much more fluidic and realistic, especially at the tougher difficulty levels (if you are a DBC 14 veteran, don't be afraid to crank up the AI), bowling is tougher than before, but much more rewarding, once you get the hang of it, and fielding has been pushed up a couple of notches for the good. The interface remains simplistic, and focuses on getting you in the game as soon as possible. There are still no licensed players, but the fledgling community should take care of that. The career mode is much more comprehensive now, and slightly less frustrating than before (again, this depends on how it is evolved during the game's) life cycle.However, the improvements end here, at least for now. For a game priced at par with AAA titles, DBC 17 lacks production flair. A little more colour to the presentation would have done wonders, especially in the moments leading up to or after a match. Commentary is abysmal - there is no other word for it - with drab voices, unexcited commentators, and frequently messed up lines. Over time, you will realise how the bad commentary actually kills half the fun to be had out of the match. Animations could have been spruced up much more, and the fluidity could have been worked upon. It's not that the end game is bad, just that three years and a AAA price were enough for anyone to expect all the previous issues ironed out, and substantial improvements put in.While I can easily recommend this game to a DBC newbie / cricket enthusiast (assuming you are okay shelling out this kind of money), I will be hard pressed to do so to anyone who has played DBC 14. The game needs a couple of updates and major patches before it deserves that credit. I will be sure to update my review if and when that happens."
76561198397255933,Recommended,464850,33538663,Posted: 14 July,all,Commandandbefree,"What a FANTASTIC achievement. I'm a huge cricket fan and student of the game, and didn't think a video game would capture the subtleties of cricket, but, it does, it so does. 14 was playable but flawed, struggle to find the flaws with this one. The minor ones that come to mind include frustrating field changes by ai, the strike changes with some stumpings which is weird, the women seem to have super thin arms and and could use some more designing work. Biggest flaw is the field resets, especially in competition mode. Some, behind the scenes (news clippings, buzz on the circuit over a performance, maybe someday clips from cricketers) would be AWESOME in the career mode but it is incredibly cool as it is.Now for the good. In listing the jumps from 14, leg glance dominance is gone, edges are now a thing, run outs are more intuitive (keep rt and nothing else pressed, otherwise the runners do wierd things), the super-fielder problem is gone (great work done wrt problem) but best of all. SPIN IS THE WINNER, it is artistic and varied, though you need to figure out how to add a quicker one in there. The commentary is exponentially better but little things like speaking of overthrows like shots, anti climactic last ball commentary etc (ideally you should add specific commentary/lines for the end of matches).This ended up being longer than I planned but these are my thoughts of the top of my head. I'm not a gamer per se, just very into cricket and I'd recommend learning this for any lover of the game."
