,Recommended,464850,32117217,Posted: 1 June,all,Radiator,"Pros:You'll be hard pressed to find a cricket game as in depth as thisEvery shot and every ball in the book can be played or bowledSmack Jadeja's bowling back over his headBowl KP middle stump as he tries to hoik you over square legRemove people you don't like from your side once you become CaptainVery detailed player creation and as a result...Community created national and international teams, players, bats and stadiums are fantasticCons:Insanely buggy and unreliable in so many waysAnimations don't work properly half the timeControl inputs can be totally unresponsive, more often when batting than bowlingBatting and bowling feedback flat out liesIncredibly unintuitive menu systemAs lovely as James Taylor is, the commentary gets incredibly annoying after a whileDon Bradman Cricket 17 is, like the game of cricket itself, a strange beast.  Capable of being extremely satisfying and highly frustrating in equal measures, I certainly wouldn't call it a polished game, even a couple of months from release and several patches.  As a bowler, tail end batsmen will occasionally happily despatch your 148kph inswinging yorkers back over your head for 4 or 6, or as a batsman you'll find your character leave their ground and get themselves run out when you told them not to.  The game will give you feedback saying you hit a perfectly timed and executed shot only for the ball to limply pootle through the air towards a fielder where the catch is easily taken, and for some reason the control inputs for trying to play (specifically) a front foot leg glance will make the player character teleport a foot or so to his right and get bowled without ever getting close to touching the ball.However, it seems to be of equal likeliness to these freak events that everything can go extremely well for you, once you've broken out of the silly ""club"" stage which sees you have to play T20 cricket (even if you wanted your player to be the second coming of Rahul Dravid and grind the opposition bowling down via attritional defensive play.)  Getting into a national competition like the County Championship (English) Sheffield Shield (Australian) or Ranji Trophy (India) among others is where the game really begins as you can really use the scale of those competitions to play your character in however you like, whether they be a specialist batsman or bowler, all-rounder or even a wicket-keeper.  Personally I've tried to make my player a bit like Kent legend Darren Stevens; a useful middle order batsman and wily medium pace bowler, and to its credit DBC 17 is happy for me to do that; as the game allows you when batting to fine tune shot selection you can block away as much as you like and then completely surprise the opposition by playing something like a slog sweep or ramp shot, and everything in between is possible... just unfortunately sometimes it just doesn't work properly.DBC 17 is likely as faithful a recreation of the game of cricket as can be achieved in a video game, although admittedly I haven't played its highly lauded predecessor, and although I only play village cricket myself I have watched a lot of cricket on television and in person, and I've never seen a slip fielder, from a standing start, slide three metres to their right to take a low catch off the outside edge. Nor have I seen the mid-off fielder throw down the stumps while clearly not looking in the right direction or even moving their torso, having gathered the ball mere nanoseconds before.  I mean, Ab de Villiers is good, but he's not THAT good."
